        <productionVolumeComment xml:lang="en">In year 2000 the EU provides a production volume between 5 and10 thousand tonnes. We assume the average to be the total production: 7500 tonnes.

The yearly growth rate of production of chemicals is given by the European Chemical Industry Council to be 0.2% between 2000 and 2010. This allows to estimate the production for year 2005.
(http://www.cefic.org/Global/Facts-and-figures-images/Graphs%202011/FF2011-chapters-PDF/Cefic_FF%20Rapport%202011_3_Growth_Compet.pdf)

The Global production volume is obtained with the GDP ratio (in current US$) as published in the World Bank. This is calculated as : GDPworld/GDP EU. The ratio is 3.3

For calculating the amount produced in this specific technology, there are 2 main arguments:
(1)The Ullmann chemicals encyclopedia states that at present NaF is frequently prepared from inexpensive materials such as the waste gases from superphosphate manufacture. The chemical can also be obtained from sodium carbonate. 

(2)The US Encyclopedia of Chemicals, Drugs, and Biologicals states that "normally" it is manufactured by the reaction of hydrofluoric acid with soda ash (sodium carbonate) or caustic soda (sodium hydroxide), It also referes to 2 other production routes, namely by neutralizing aqueous hydrogen fluoride with sodium bicarbonate and by fusing cryolite with sodium hydroxide.

We assume 40% is created from "inexpensive materials", and 60% equally with sodium carbonate and sodium hydroxide.

Note: the global production calculations were crosschecked with production data for US and Japan, which gave results in the same range and confirms the validity of this estimation.</productionVolumeComment>
